Block Sensitive Data in Chats

Sensitive data rules let you block specific patterns, such as credit card, Social Security, phone and account numbers, or even profanity. You can choose to remove the text or replace it with your preferred characters.

Available in: Salesforce Classic and Lightning Experience
Available in: Performance Editions and in Developer Edition orgs that were created after June 14, 2012
Available in: Essentials, Unlimited, and Enterprise Editions with Service Cloud or Sales Cloud

To create sensitive data rules:
Customize Application

IMPORTANT The legacy chat product is scheduled for retirement on February 14, 2026. You can continue to use chat but we no longer recommend implementing new chat channels.

In Setup, enter Sensitive Data in the Quick Find box, then select Sensitive Data Rules.
Click New or New Sensitive Data Rule.
Write each pattern as a JavaScript regular expression (regex), and choose your preferred settings. The regex is case-sensitive.
Optionally, test your pattern.
Enter some text in the format of the data you want to block.
Preview your results to ensure that the rule is working correctly.
Select the roles for which you want to enforce this rule.
Set a priority for the rule. Lower numbers are executed first.
Click Save.

When a rule is triggered, it logs one or more of these chat transcript events:
Sensitive data blocked (Agent)
Sensitive data blocked (Supervisor)
Sensitive data blocked (Visitor)

Sensitive data rules apply to the auto-greeting and any quick text that you have enabled. They donâ€™t apply to the agent name or other standard text in the chat window.

You can block the text from agents, supervisors, customers, or all of these.
title: Blocking Sensitive Data in Chats
